2
00:01:04,898 --> 00:01:10,968
West Berlin, 1945

3
00:01:18,808 --> 00:01:19,988
Passport.

4
00:01:35,228 --> 00:01:36,988
Nice car!

5
00:01:37,158 --> 00:01:39,195
Where did you get it from?

6
00:01:39,282 --> 00:01:40,675
It's a Wagen from Switzerland.

7
00:01:41,738 --> 00:01:42,978
It's like you?

8
00:01:43,048 --> 00:01:44,055
like me.

9
00:01:47,238 --> 00:01:49,938
It's a Wagen Switzerland!
The girl too!

10
00:01:54,921 --> 00:01:55,938
I wanna see your face.

11
00:01:57,955 --> 00:01:58,938
Can I talk to you?

12
00:02:02,238 --> 00:02:03,338
Common she's not Eva Braun.

13
00:02:04,428 --> 00:02:07,078
Of course not! The bitch
got killed by her husband!

14
00:02:07,538 --> 00:02:09,678
She's from the camps.

15
00:02:16,438 --> 00:02:17,338
Show me your face.

16
00:02:17,438 --> 00:02:17,935
Please.

17
00:02:18,035 --> 00:02:19,045
Shut up!

18
00:02:19,745 --> 00:02:21,045
Show me your face, now!

19
00:02:34,945 --> 00:02:36,008
Sorry.

20
00:02:38,915 --> 00:02:40,600
It's okay.

21
00:02:46,700 --> 00:02:48,100
Let 'em pass!

22
00:03:25,068 --> 00:03:27,443
The wound canal is
from a gunshot.

23
00:03:28,568 --> 00:03:31,651
They thought you were dead.
You were lucky.

24
00:03:33,276 --> 00:03:34,734
Can you see?

25
00:03:36,901 --> 00:03:38,068
That's good.

26
00:03:38,609 --> 00:03:41,526
The patient has wound fever.
Intravenous penicillin.

27
00:03:43,984 --> 00:03:46,484
Cheekbone and nasal
bone are shattered.

28
00:03:46,943 --> 00:03:49,109
Chipping to the
left cranial bone.

29
00:03:50,609 --> 00:03:52,401
You were a singer?

30
00:03:55,401 --> 00:03:56,734
Where was that?

31
00:03:57,401 --> 00:04:00,526
Most recently at the St.Michaels choir.
In London?

32
00:04:00,734 --> 00:04:02,693
Yes.
When?

33
00:04:03,568 --> 00:04:04,901
Up to '38.

34
00:04:05,693 --> 00:04:08,443
Then you, a Jewess, returned here.
Why?

35
00:04:15,109 --> 00:04:17,526
They have wonderfully
cool cellars.

36
00:04:19,401 --> 00:04:21,568
And there's a real
plantation in the park.

37
00:04:23,193 --> 00:04:24,901
We'll soon be able
to walk around.

38
00:04:25,318 --> 00:04:28,484
And you'll be able to...
Who's paying for this, Lene?

39
00:04:30,734 --> 00:04:33,068
You?
No.

40
00:04:35,151 --> 00:04:36,526
You inherited.

41
00:04:39,609 --> 00:04:41,651
Your entire family is dead.

42
00:04:46,609 --> 00:04:48,234
And Herbert and Marie...

43
00:04:50,776 --> 00:04:52,776
the twins...
Esther?

44
00:04:55,901 --> 00:04:57,234
I haven't found her yet.

45
00:05:16,651 --> 00:05:18,068
Where is Johnny?

46
00:05:20,901 --> 00:05:22,693
So how do you
want to look?

47
00:05:22,901 --> 00:05:24,359
It's your choice.

48
00:05:24,568 --> 00:05:27,443
Some of my patients
favor Zarah Leander,

49
00:05:28,276 --> 00:05:29,568
others Miss Soderbaum.

50
00:05:30,484 --> 00:05:32,651
I guess they're both
out of fashion now.

51
00:05:33,609 --> 00:05:37,901
A few gentlemen out there would
probably like new faces, too.

52
00:05:38,818 --> 00:05:40,818
I want to look like I used to.

53
00:05:42,526 --> 00:05:46,151
That's difficult.
I recommend you think it over.

54
00:05:46,609 --> 00:05:47,609
Why?

55
00:05:47,818 --> 00:05:50,526
On the one hand,
it's never quite the same,

56
00:05:50,734 --> 00:05:53,943
and on the other, a new
face is an advantage.

57
00:05:55,984 --> 00:05:59,776
How is it an advantage?
You'll be a new and different person.

58
00:06:00,193 --> 00:06:02,484
You won't be identifiable,
which means...

59
00:06:02,651 --> 00:06:05,151
I want to look exactly
like I used to.

60
00:06:11,359 --> 00:06:14,401
You'll receive an
intravenous anesthetic.

61
00:06:14,568 --> 00:06:17,901
An ether mask can't be used
due to your face's condition,

62
00:06:18,151 --> 00:06:21,151
but don't be concerned,
you'll sleep deeply.

63
00:06:22,193 --> 00:06:24,318
Just count backwards: ten...

64
00:06:24,901 --> 00:06:26,193
nine, eight, etc.

65
00:06:26,401 --> 00:06:29,276
Know what the Americans call it?
A 'countdown'.

66
00:06:29,484 --> 00:06:32,818
It comes from a German film,
'Woman in the Moon'.

67
00:06:34,901 --> 00:06:36,776
So now count, ten...

68
00:06:37,443 --> 00:06:38,526
Ten.
Nine...

69
00:06:39,109 --> 00:06:40,609
Nine.
Carry on.

70
00:06:40,818 --> 00:06:42,526
Eight, seven...

71
00:06:43,568 --> 00:06:45,943
six, five...

72
00:10:03,151 --> 00:10:05,359
JEW. JEW.
JEW...

73
00:10:20,955 --> 00:10:21,959
Sir!

74
00:10:28,473 --> 00:10:31,559
Sir! What the hell do
you think you're doing?

75
00:10:49,959 --> 00:10:51,059
Excuse me?!

76
00:10:51,159 --> 00:10:54,759
Oh Sorry! Lene Winter
from the agency.

77
00:10:54,859 --> 00:10:56,899
What happened?

78
00:10:58,100 --> 00:11:00,899
He's trying to shanghai
something in the cards.

79
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:02,989
Well, he's not the only one.
Hmm?

80
00:11:03,079 --> 00:11:04,689
Can I have a look?

81
00:11:04,789 --> 00:11:05,796
Go ahead.

82
00:11:16,359 --> 00:11:19,234
Johannes Lenz, Pianist - Divorced
October 04,1944

83
00:11:29,693 --> 00:11:31,776
That's already
looking really good.

84
00:11:43,359 --> 00:11:46,109
A couple of days and
the bandages come off.

85
00:11:49,693 --> 00:11:51,609
I found an apartment,
by the way.

86
00:11:52,901 --> 00:11:53,943
In Haifa.

87
00:11:56,068 --> 00:11:57,443
You can see the sea.

88
00:11:58,609 --> 00:12:01,484
Beautiful, simple
lined architecture.

89
00:12:01,651 --> 00:12:03,443
Bernstein designed it.

90
00:12:04,734 --> 00:12:06,359
I've got photos.
Want a look?

91
00:12:10,068 --> 00:12:11,193
Here.

92
00:12:29,484 --> 00:12:30,776
No, I didn't see him.

93
00:12:45,193 --> 00:12:48,401
Nelly, it was bombed out.
It no longer exists.

94
00:14:03,526 --> 00:14:04,776
I no longer exist.

95
00:14:11,484 --> 00:14:14,193
Nelly, remember how you
felt three months ago?

96
00:14:16,276 --> 00:14:17,776
How desperate you were?

97
00:14:20,484 --> 00:14:22,776
It's extraordinary
what Dr.Bongartz...

98
00:14:26,484 --> 00:14:30,818
In a few days the bandages come off...
Would you recognize me?

99
00:14:32,234 --> 00:14:34,568
Would you recognize me?

100
00:14:34,776 --> 00:14:36,193
Yes.

101
00:14:37,651 --> 00:14:38,943
No.

102
00:14:44,109 --> 00:14:45,484
This is me.

103
00:14:47,651 --> 00:14:49,276
Where did you get that?

104
00:14:54,609 --> 00:14:57,693
The clinic needed pictures
for the reconstruction.

105
00:15:01,901 --> 00:15:03,943
Sorry, that's the wrong word.

106
00:15:04,276 --> 00:15:06,443
Dr.Bongartz used
it and I simply...

107
00:15:08,984 --> 00:15:11,734
Re-creation is better, right?
Re-creation.

108
00:15:12,068 --> 00:15:14,193
Just look at me.

109
00:15:15,526 --> 00:15:17,193
Nelly, you're beautiful.

110
00:15:19,651 --> 00:15:21,901
That's not the point.

111
00:15:25,193 --> 00:15:26,818
What do the circles signify?

112
00:15:28,068 --> 00:15:29,276
Those are Nazis.

113
00:15:36,276 --> 00:15:38,651
And the crosses
are for the dead?

114
00:15:39,318 --> 00:15:40,484
Yes.

115
00:15:42,193 --> 00:15:44,234
We need a cross
above Esther, too.

116
00:15:50,318 --> 00:15:52,401
It's such a miracle
you survived.

117
00:16:03,776 --> 00:16:05,526
There's no cross
above Johnny.

118
00:16:05,984 --> 00:16:07,401
Johnny doesn't interest me.

119
00:16:19,234 --> 00:16:20,693
Here are dresses,

120
00:16:22,359 --> 00:16:24,276
a jacket of English cloth,

121
00:16:24,651 --> 00:16:27,693
and there are two coats,
a summer one and a lined one,

122
00:16:27,901 --> 00:16:29,151
to get you started.

123
00:16:29,651 --> 00:16:31,609
It was all acquired
by Mrs. Winter.

124
00:16:32,109 --> 00:16:33,568
Wonderful cloth.

125
00:16:35,151 --> 00:16:36,568
You're a size 38, right?

126
00:16:38,984 --> 00:16:40,943
And when are you
going to Palestine?

127
00:16:43,818 --> 00:16:45,276
I don't know yet.

128
00:16:48,693 --> 00:16:50,359
So, this is the bathroom,

129
00:16:50,818 --> 00:16:52,526
all fully equipped,

130
00:16:53,609 --> 00:16:55,151
and in perfect
working order.

131
00:16:55,818 --> 00:16:58,151
If you need anything,
please let me know.

132
00:17:02,651 --> 00:17:04,776
No, that we won't do.

133
00:17:05,526 --> 00:17:06,901
The light stays off.

134
00:17:07,609 --> 00:17:10,609
We have a real
plague of flies.

135
00:17:11,359 --> 00:17:14,234
The war didn't seem
to bother them at all.

136
00:17:14,568 --> 00:17:16,693
They come up from
the lake in swarms.

137
00:17:21,401 --> 00:17:24,151
No, please don't,
I'd rather do it myself.

138
00:17:25,734 --> 00:17:30,068
When do we dine, Elisabeth?
At seven, if it please you, Ma'am.

139
00:17:30,276 --> 00:17:34,068
What have you cooked for us?
Stuffed cabbage with sweetbread.

140
00:17:34,276 --> 00:17:36,234
Where did the
sweetbread come from?

141
00:17:36,859 --> 00:17:39,193
I have no nutmeg, no butter,

142
00:17:39,609 --> 00:17:41,401
no black pepper, it's awful.

143
00:17:42,234 --> 00:17:44,193
But you improvise
so wonderfully.

144
00:17:44,401 --> 00:17:46,526
Improvise, improvise!

145
00:17:47,984 --> 00:17:50,443
I've had it with improvising.

146
00:17:54,734 --> 00:17:56,526
Elisabeth is really a gem.

147
00:17:57,901 --> 00:18:01,193
She's not a Nazi?
She always hated the Nazis.

148
00:18:05,901 --> 00:18:07,318
So, you like it?

149
00:18:10,109 --> 00:18:11,151
Yes.

150
00:18:11,984 --> 00:18:13,151
Great.

151
00:18:14,943 --> 00:18:18,693
By the way, I put the papers for
the Haifa apartment on the desk.

152
00:18:20,276 --> 00:18:23,526
And I found two other
for us in Tel Aviv.

153
00:18:24,484 --> 00:18:28,276
One is on a housing project.
We're being allocated terrain.

154
00:18:38,609 --> 00:18:41,318
You know, it wasn't easy
getting us both a visa.

155
00:19:06,609 --> 00:19:08,526
So, there.
Thank you, Elisabeth.

156
00:19:47,568 --> 00:19:48,943
Can you manage?

157
00:19:49,193 --> 00:19:50,401
Yes.

158
00:20:01,359 --> 00:20:02,943
Can I hear that again?

159
00:20:05,526 --> 00:20:06,901
It's nice, huh?

160
00:20:24,568 --> 00:20:27,526
I'd listened to it in London
before falling asleep.

161
00:20:35,818 --> 00:20:37,484
Would you sing it for me?

162
00:20:42,568 --> 00:20:43,693
Okay.

163
00:20:48,526 --> 00:20:50,818
I can't stand German
songs anymore.

164
00:20:57,901 --> 00:21:00,776
When you're better, we'll
take care of your assets.

165
00:21:06,443 --> 00:21:07,526
Is it a lot?

166
00:21:09,359 --> 00:21:12,026
They're substantial.
It'll take a while...

167
00:21:12,234 --> 00:21:17,026
to get the Nazis out of the properties,
but there's lots of money in Switzerland.

168
00:21:17,318 --> 00:21:20,859
It's the victims' money,
it brings an obligation.

169
00:21:21,943 --> 00:21:23,568
To do what?

170
00:21:27,943 --> 00:21:32,568
To go to Palestine and found a
state where we Jews can live safely.

171
00:21:33,609 --> 00:21:36,109
To do so, we take back
all they took away.

172
00:21:38,234 --> 00:21:41,359
Maybe then we can sing and
hear German songs again.

173
00:22:54,901 --> 00:22:56,318
Did you like it?

174
00:22:58,318 --> 00:22:59,401
Yes.

175
00:23:00,109 --> 00:23:01,484
Then give me something.

176
00:23:03,276 --> 00:23:04,234
Yes.

177
00:23:15,943 --> 00:23:17,443
I'm looking for my husband.

178
00:23:19,734 --> 00:23:21,193
He's a musician, too.

179
00:23:22,526 --> 00:23:23,859
What does he play?

180
00:23:26,109 --> 00:23:27,526
He's a pianist.

181
00:23:28,359 --> 00:23:31,651
If he's lucky, he'll be in
one of the cabarets or clubs.

182
00:23:32,484 --> 00:23:35,693
If not, he'll be on the
corner with an accordion.

183
00:23:39,734 --> 00:23:41,318
What clubs?

184
00:23:42,401 --> 00:23:44,234
I'd try the American sector.

185
00:24:52,818 --> 00:24:54,359
Johnny, what did I do?

186
00:24:55,151 --> 00:24:56,818
I just wanted
to dance a bit.

187
00:24:57,734 --> 00:25:00,109
Let go of me! Johnny!
Get off me!

188
00:26:19,909 --> 00:26:20,919
Johnny!

189
00:26:30,234 --> 00:26:31,193
Yes.

190
00:26:35,693 --> 00:26:40,068
Excuse me.
I mistook you for someone.

191
00:26:41,234 --> 00:26:42,693
Stay where you are.

192
00:26:44,276 --> 00:26:46,234
I told you to
stop right there.

193
00:27:04,151 --> 00:27:06,193
What do you have
in your bag?

194
00:27:07,693 --> 00:27:09,109
Show me.

195
00:27:26,359 --> 00:27:27,776
The fine coat!

196
00:27:29,859 --> 00:27:32,276
I'll never remove that.

197
00:27:33,401 --> 00:27:34,734
That's tar.

198
00:27:35,568 --> 00:27:37,443
Where was she gallivanting?

199
00:27:38,901 --> 00:27:41,443
Would you leave us for
a moment, Elisabeth?

200
00:27:48,526 --> 00:27:49,943
So, did you meet him?

201
00:27:53,734 --> 00:27:57,609
You can't just wander around at night.
There are all sorts out.

202
00:27:57,818 --> 00:27:59,401
I don't go out
without a revolver.

203
00:28:01,318 --> 00:28:04,401
I can't always look after you,
I have to go to Poland soon.

204
00:28:04,609 --> 00:28:07,026
I might be there a while.
How long?

205
00:28:08,359 --> 00:28:10,943
A week, two,
maybe longer.

206
00:28:16,568 --> 00:28:19,109
Did you give thought
to Haifa or Tel Aviv?

207
00:28:21,109 --> 00:28:24,443
In Tel Aviv there's a Jewish
choir run by Vera Stroux.

208
00:28:24,609 --> 00:28:27,734
It might suit you.
What would I do in a Jewish choir?

209
00:28:27,943 --> 00:28:31,109
I'm not a Jew.
You are, like it or not.

210
00:28:31,818 --> 00:28:34,318
They tried to kill you
because you're a Jew.

211
00:28:34,693 --> 00:28:36,734
We can't remain here, Nelly.

212
00:28:58,526 --> 00:29:00,109
Johnny betrayed you.

213
00:29:04,734 --> 00:29:07,901
You were arrested
on October 6, 1944.

214
00:29:09,276 --> 00:29:11,776
Johnny was arrested
on October 4, 1944.

215
00:29:11,984 --> 00:29:16,651
He was interrogated and released
just after your arrest on October 6.

216
00:29:17,234 --> 00:29:20,193
He wasn't put in prison.
No punishment. Indeed...

217
00:29:21,109 --> 00:29:24,276
he was allowed to play again...
now he wants your money.

218
00:29:24,484 --> 00:29:26,109
Did you see him?

219
00:29:27,276 --> 00:29:29,526
Yes.
When?

220
00:29:31,651 --> 00:29:33,234
Two months ago.

221
00:29:37,651 --> 00:29:39,484
Did you speak to him?

222
00:29:40,943 --> 00:29:42,609
I don't speak to traitors.

223
00:30:24,193 --> 00:30:25,818
Shop window mannequin.

224
00:30:26,568 --> 00:30:28,859
Wonderful!
Wonderful!

225
00:30:29,609 --> 00:30:31,151
We have beer.

226
00:30:31,609 --> 00:30:34,068
We have cold beer.
We have whisky.

227
00:30:34,943 --> 00:30:36,609
We have champagne.

228
00:30:43,359 --> 00:30:48,609
And now our delightful
Vicky and Lola

229
00:30:49,234 --> 00:30:52,193
will sing the one and
only Cole Porter's...

230
00:30:52,901 --> 00:30:54,318
'Night and Day'.

231
00:30:54,651 --> 00:30:56,568
Night and day.

232
00:31:05,234 --> 00:31:09,526
♪ Night and day ♪
♪ I think of you ♪

233
00:31:10,901 --> 00:31:16,151
♪ Countless weeks have passed ♪
♪ And I just pined for you ♪

234
00:31:16,609 --> 00:31:21,859
♪ From the dreams I have at night ♪
♪ I awake each morning once again ♪

235
00:31:22,151 --> 00:31:27,359
♪ And have your sweet image ♪
♪ Before me still ♪

236
00:31:28,109 --> 00:31:32,484
♪ Wherever I am ♪
♪ I am with you ♪

237
00:31:33,776 --> 00:31:38,401
♪ I often hear your familiar ♪
♪ steps Stop at my door ♪

238
00:31:39,943 --> 00:31:45,026
♪ And the twinkle of your eyes ♪
♪ Lights the dark hours... ♪

239
00:31:45,234 --> 00:31:47,401
♪ of my loneliness ♪

240
00:31:48,568 --> 00:31:50,651
♪ Vivaciously ♪

241
00:31:51,109 --> 00:31:56,234
♪ Night and day ♪
♪ I feel that beloved hand ♪

242
00:31:56,901 --> 00:32:01,734
♪ That you softly gave me ♪
♪ As we stood by the meadow-side ♪

243
00:32:02,943 --> 00:32:05,609
♪ Of my hopes ♪
♪ you the mirage ♪

244
00:32:05,818 --> 00:32:10,526
♪ That vanishes on my approach ♪
♪ My pining stays unassuaged ♪

245
00:32:11,276 --> 00:32:13,568
♪ Night and day ♪

246
00:32:14,609 --> 00:32:15,651
♪ Like the rain... ♪

247
00:32:15,859 --> 00:32:16,818
Johnny!

248
00:32:17,568 --> 00:32:20,276
♪ When the autumn ♪
♪ mists fall leaden ♪

249
00:32:20,484 --> 00:32:22,901
♪ As the wind, ♪
♪ it screeching, cries ♪

250
00:32:23,401 --> 00:32:26,193
♪ Clouds, gray and ♪
♪ ragged, fly by ♪

251
00:32:26,401 --> 00:32:31,776
♪ My heart beats hasty paces ♪
♪ Beats and finds no rest at all ♪

252
00:32:32,776 --> 00:32:35,193
♪ Like a wailing ♪
♪ wind it whispers ♪

253
00:32:35,401 --> 00:32:38,318
♪ Just you, you, you ♪

254
00:32:38,418 --> 00:32:44,418
♪ Night and day ♪
♪ You're the one ♪

255
00:32:49,918 --> 00:32:51,738
Watch out!
You could be older!

256
00:33:30,401 --> 00:33:31,818
Nelly?

257
00:33:33,401 --> 00:33:34,526
Everything okay?

258
00:33:37,276 --> 00:33:38,443
Yes.

259
00:33:40,318 --> 00:33:42,109
One second,
I'll be right back.

260
00:33:57,734 --> 00:33:59,318
I got you a revolver, too.

261
00:34:01,693 --> 00:34:03,026
Know how to use it?

262
00:34:06,234 --> 00:34:08,484
Sometimes just showing
it is enough.

263
00:34:55,568 --> 00:34:56,901
I'm looking for Johnny.

264
00:35:00,568 --> 00:35:02,734
Did he gave you
those black eyes?

265
00:35:04,651 --> 00:35:06,068
He works here.

266
00:35:06,776 --> 00:35:08,609
There's no Johnny here.

267
00:35:13,734 --> 00:35:17,401
But I saw him.
I don't know a Johnny. Do you?

268
00:35:19,151 --> 00:35:22,484
Johnny, you swine,
your pockets are empty

269
00:35:22,734 --> 00:35:25,693
But the cellar is full,
so really there's plenty

270
00:35:25,943 --> 00:35:29,484
The world is a quay
all covered with girls

271
00:35:29,693 --> 00:35:33,526
The sailors go cross-eyed
when they give them a twirl

272
00:35:43,693 --> 00:35:45,526
How about a coffee?
Or two?

273
00:35:45,693 --> 00:35:47,818
Coming up.
Are you Johnny?

274
00:35:48,068 --> 00:35:51,026
The doll here wants work.
But don't hit her again.

275
00:35:51,234 --> 00:35:53,151
Johannes,
get a move on!

276
00:35:56,568 --> 00:35:58,401
He's the one
to speak to, Miss.

